DADOS-BASICOS-DO-TRABALHO.TITULO-DO-TRABALHO-INGLES: Fragmentation of cholesterol and oxysterols by atmospheric pressure chemical ionization tandem mass spectrometry (APCI-MS/MS): a preliminary study

DETALHAMENTO-DO-TRABALHO.NOME-DO-EVENTO: Terceiro Congresso Brasileiro de Espectrometria de Massas
DETALHAMENTO-DO-TRABALHO.TITULO-DOS-ANAIS-OU-PROCEEDINGS: Fragmentation of cholesterol and oxysterols by atmospheric pressure chemical ionization tandem mass spectrometry (APCI-MS/MS): a preliminary study

INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS.DESCRICAO-INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS-INGLES: Cholesterol is susceptible to oxidation in presence of light, oxygen and high storage temperature.1 The cholesterol oxidation products (or ?oxysterols?) can be found in many processed dairy, meat and egg products. They have been reported to have atherogenic, cytotoxic, mutagenic and carcinogenic effects in both in vivo and in vitro studies.2 Liquid chromatography mass spectrometry (LC-MS and LC-MS/MS) has emerged as a very useful analytical technique for the analysis of cholesterol and oxysterols in foodstuffs, as an alternative to gas chromatography mass spectrometry (GC-MS).2 The aim of this study is to investigate the fragmentation of cholesterol and eight oxysterols using atmospheric pressure chemical ionization mass spectrometry (APCI-MS), aiming to achieve structure-fragmentation relationships to be used in the structural elucidation of oxysterols by LC-MS/MS. Mass spectral analyses were undertaken in an ion trap mass spectrometer fitted with a APCI source. All of the compounds were analyzed using the same experimental conditions. Proton affinities were obtained using computational calculations at B3LYP/6-31G(2df,p)//HF/6-31G(d) level. These values demonstrated that cholesterol is protonated at the oxygen hydroxyl, thus leading to the water elimination. Further fragmentation of [M+H-H2O]+ ion involves typical pericyclic reactions and 1,4-hydrogen rearrangements. The investigation of the fragmentation patterns of the selected oxysterols are in progress.
